## EU–UK Trade and Cooperation Agreement

The [EU–UK Trade and Cooperation Agreement](EU%E2%80%93UK_Trade_and_Cooperation_Agreement) is a trade deal between the [European Union](/wiki/European_Union) and the [United Kingdom](/wiki/United_Kingdom), signed on [December 30, 2020](/wiki/December_30). This agreement essentially outlines the terms of [trade](/wiki/Trade) and cooperation between the two entities following the [United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union](/wiki/United_Kingdom%27s_withdrawal_from_the_European_Union) on [January 31, 2020](/wiki/January_31). It’s a rather complex document, as one might expect when disentangling decades of intertwined policies and economies. The agreement covers a vast array of subjects, from the seemingly mundane details of [customs](/wiki/Customs) and [tariffs](/wiki/Tariff) to more intricate matters like [data protection](/wiki/Data_protection), [intellectual property](/wiki/Intellectual_property), and even [fisheries](/wiki/Fisheries). It was negotiated under the shadow of an impending deadline, a characteristic of many diplomatic endeavors, where the pressure of time often forces concessions and compromises that might otherwise be avoided. The signing itself was a formality, a punctuation mark at the end of a long and often acrimonious negotiation process.

